title: Andrew Schwenke
text:
Quantitative ecologist and software developer. I like to work on software and data solutions that can solve environmental challenges and support research.
Over ten years of experience with the R programming language. I excel in using data to uncover insights into systems, such as environmental effects on animal behaviours and species distributions.
My current focus is expanding my skill set by learning computer science and different tech stacks, including Go, Typescript, React + Django + PostgreSQL stack, and Ruby.




Take a look at my projects →




Take a look at my posts and notes →








Serra do Cipó, Brazil

title: Colours
text:
Colours
Tags: colours palettes ggplot2 colors
Colours and colour palettes.

library(paletteer)
pal_orange <- paletteer_d("ggsci::deep_orange_material", 10)
pal_dy <- paletteer_c("grDevices::Dynamic", 16)
pal_gr <- paletteer_c("grDevices::Grays", 12)

pal_ter <- paletteer_c("grDevices::Terrain 2", 16)
# Reverse
pal_red <- paletteer_c("grDevices::Reds 3", 12, -1)

title: Spatial
text:
Tags: plot point gps location
Add a single coordinate, like if you wanted to add one or more locations to a map plot ad-hoc.

bendigo <- c(-36.7596, 144.2786)

df <- data.frame(x = bendigo[2], y = bendigo[1])
bendigo <- sf::st_as_sf(df, coords = c("x", "y"), crs = 4326) |>
  sf::st_transform(3577)

# make this a simple feature with name Bendigo and geometry
bendigo <- bendigo |>
  dplyr::mutate(name = "Bendigo")



Combine two categorical rasters by concatenating their levels:

r <- terra::rast(nrows = 10, ncols = 10)
terra::values(r) <- sample(3, terra::ncell(r), replace = TRUE)
levels(r) <- data.frame(id = 1:3, cover = c("forest", "water", "urban"))
terra::plot(r)






rr <- terra::rast(r)
terra::values(rr) <- sample(1:3, terra::ncell(rr), replace = TRUE)
levels(rr) <- data.frame(id = c(1:3), color = c("red", "green", "blue"))
terra::plot(rr)






x <- terra::concats(r, rr)
terra::levels(x)[[1]]

  ID  cover_color
1  0   forest_red
2  1 forest_green
3  2  forest_blue
4  3    water_red
5  4  water_green
6  5   water_blue
7  6    urban_red
8  7  urban_green
9  8   urban_blue

terra::plot(x)
